Let $B: \mathbb{R}^2 \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$ be a differentiable function that represents the amount of honey produced (in kilograms) by a beekeeper, where the two variables are the average temperature (in Celsius) and average rainfall (in millimeters) during the honey production season. Assume that the average temperature and rainfall are always positive.

The beekeeper notices that when the average temperature is fixed at $T$ degrees, the amount of honey produced reaches a maximum when the average rainfall is $R$ millimeters. Similarly, when the average rainfall is fixed at $R$ millimeters, the amount of honey produced reaches a maximum when the average temperature is $T$ degrees.

If the temperature and rainfall during a particular season were both equal to $T$ and $R$ respectively, show that
\[\nabla^2 B(T, R) = 
\begin{bmatrix}
\frac{\partial^2 B}{\partial T^2} & \frac{\partial^2 B}{\partial T \partial R} \\
\frac{\partial^2 B}{\partial R \partial T} & \frac{\partial^2 B}{\partial R^2}
\end{bmatrix}
\]
is a negative semidefinite matrix.
